[2
Date: 1 Aug 2000 10:20:27 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: M2 Communications Ltd., 1 Aug 2000 [edited

VIRGINIA DEPT OF AGRICULTURE AND CONSUMER SERVICES:
In the last 2 weeks, 6 horses died in the Chesapeake and Suffolk area with
central nervous system symptoms have been referred to the Virginia
Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services' Regional Animal Health
Laboratory System for testing. Testing is not yet complete, but 3 of those
horses exhibited microscopic changes in the brain indicating a viral
encephalitis problem. Two of the horses have not yet had their brains
examined microscopically, and 1 horse had no microscopic evidence of
encephalitis.
Samples from all 6 horses have been sent to the U.S. Department of
Agriculture's (USDA) National Veterinary Services Laboratory (NVSL) in
Ames, Iowa for virus isolation and identification attempts.
Even though veterinary officials caution the current outbreak has not yet
been confirmed to be Eastern Equine Encephalitis (EEE), they recommend
horse owners vaccinate their animals every 6 to 12 months against the
disease. This is particularly important in the Southeastern region of
Virginia, where they recommend the 6-month vaccination interval. Although a
few cases of equine encephalitis tend to occur almost every year in
Southeastern Virginia, this is an unusually high number of cases in a short
period of time. Several possible viruses could cause this sort of
encephalitis in horses, with EEE being the most likely.
All of the equine encephalitis viruses follow a similar pattern of residing
most of the year in wild bird or mammal hosts and only becoming a problem
when there are enough mosquitoes present to transmit the virus from the
reservoir into horses or people. This in turn is related to rainfall and
temperature patterns, which this year have been favorable for the
production of mosquitoes.
Typical symptoms of encephalitis include staggering, circling, depression,
loss of appetite and sometimes fever and blindness. There is no cure for
the disease, which can kill 50-90 percent of the horses infected. Any horse
surviving the disease almost always has long term brain damage.
Fortunately, there is an excellent vaccine available to prevent this
disease in horses. The vaccine is only effective for 6 - 12 months, so
horses must be re-vaccinated at least annually and, in an area where the
disease occurs frequently, vaccination every 6 months is probably best.
Other prevention methods include destroying standing water breeding sites
for mosquitoes, use of insect repellents such as DEET, and removing animals
from mosquito infested areas during peak biting times, usually dusk to dawn.
CONTACT: Office of the State Veterinarian Tel: +1 804 786 2481
